Regression Problems

In the following exercise well use the FIFA data set containing information on 19 239 players enrolled in the season of 22, including columns related to: short_name, role, preferred_foot, player_positions, wage_eur, value_eur, overall and all attribute names starting with skill.

Modelling Aims

Our goal is to predict the values of overall of an offensive player based on information we have, such as his skill characteristics, foot preference, etc.

The process of building a regression model is simple and is referred to as model fitting. Although different types of machine learning have different approaches, there are several common steps that are used by most modelling scenarios, not just the regression ones. Be sure to include these steps to get the job done. You need to:

  • understand your data and make a good data budgeting choice (not discussed here),
  • know how to chose the modeling function with the right formula,
  • capture and extract information from any object that a modeling function creates,
  • aggregate and interpret the model performance metrics,
  • and validate your findings on fresh data.

It is ultimately up to you how you define these categories, but we can provide some hints. Offensive players are strikers ST, wingers: RW, LW (W as wingers), central forwarders CF and central attacking midfielders, or CAMs. Defensive players are LB (L as left, B as back), LWB, RB, RWB, RB and central defending midfielder CDM - these are all positions dedicated to stop the opponents advance. GK are goal keepers. Everyone else plays as midfielder..

Data Exploration

A players value stems from his overall score, but how a players score is affected by his skills? Which skill or skills make a good striker? Or which skills make a good midfielder? Is it only one skill, or a combination of many? Let find out.

Your task is to formalize a relation between the value of players skill and players score and use this formula to predict offensive players score from new data. To do that, lets inspect data for any obvious pattern:

#-----Helper functions-----
panel.cor <- function(x,y, digits=2, prefix="", cex.cor){
  usr <- par("usr")
  on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(0,1,0,1))
  r <- abs(cor(x,y,use="complete.obs"))
  txt <- format(c(r,0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
  txt <- paste0(prefix, txt,sep="")
  if(missing(cex.cor)) cex.cor <- 0.8/strwidth(txt)
  text(0.5, 0.5, txt, cex = cex.cor * (1 + r) / 2)
}

panel.hist <- function(x, ...){
  usr <- par("usr")
  on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(usr[1:2],0,1.5))
  h <- hist(x, plot = FALSE)
  breaks <- h$breaks
  nB <- length(breaks)
  y <- h$counts
  y <- y/max(y)
  rect(breaks[-nB], 0, breaks[-1], y, col="white",...)
}

panel.lm <- function(x,y,col = par("col"), bg = NA, pch = par("pch"),
                     cex = 1, col.smooth = "blue",...){
  points(x,y,pch=pch, col=col(alpha = 0.1), bg=bg, cex=cex)
  abline(stats::lm(x ~ y), col = "steelblue", ...)
}

data %>%

We can now summarize the relationship between values of all possible pairs of attributes. As skill values increase, the overall players score increases as well, and the increase can be roughly described by straight line.

Moreover, every pair of attributes seems to be correlated, implying that picking one attribute is enough to model the relation of X (independent variable skill) and Y (dependent variable overall). Since we are looking for fitting a straight line with the least scatter, we select skill_dribbling or skill_ball_control for further analysis.

Hypothesis Formulation

Skill dribbling stands for the players ability to pass through defense and get in position with the chance of scoring. It is the trait what the attackers are selected for. Lets see if our data confirms that.

The data show a fairly linear trend for each player class. However, an attacker overall value seem to be more affected by higher dribbling (the slope of a fitted line is steeper) than a defender or a midfielder. If you are into football scouting business, you might be interested in formulating two null hypotheses:

  • H0: Skill dribbling has no effect on the overall value of an offensive player.

  • H0: There is no difference between the left and right footed players (in case you are searching for new Maradona).

In the next section, we are going to investigate both by fitting a multiple regression model.

Model Fitting

Suppose that fitting an ordinary linear regression model is our choice. This is equivalent to specifying that the outcome data is numeric (which overall is) and that the predictors are related to the outcome in terms of simple slopes and intercepts. \[ y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + ...+ \beta_px_{pi} \]

To fit an ordinary linear regression model in R, you can use the lm() function. There are two important arguments to this function: a model formula and data. The formula is symbolic.

For example, the simple formula:

  • overall ~ skill_dribbling specifies that the players overall score is the outcome (since it is on the left-hand side of the tilde ~) and that the skill_dribbling value is the predictor.

The formula can be extended by adding an additional predictor; e.g.for preferred_foot, which will be internally encoded numerically. Adding foot preference information to the model does not mean that skill_dribbling and encoded class of preferred_foot are added together. This formula would symbolically represent that skill_dribbling and preferred_foot should be added as separate main effects to the model. We can use + inside the formula:

  • overall ~ skill_dribbling + preferred_foot to acknowledge the effect of two predictors. This means that for every unit we move on the axis x, there will be two additive effects impacting how much we travel on the y-axis.

Interpreting Model Coefficients

The overall attribute positively depends from skill_dribbling; for every skill point we move on the x-axis, there will be 0.68 (Estimate) +/- 0.37 (Std. Error) unit increase in overall score of a player (y-axis). A player with 0 dribbling skill will have the overall value of 21.17.

If your player is right footed, his overall value drops by 0.11 +/- 0.10 units. However, the associated P value is not statistically significant even at the level of 0.05, so there is likely no real impact of player foot preference.

Inspecting Residuals

When applied to an object of a regression model, plot() displays the analysis of residuals. It is always good to inspect these data to make sure that your theoretical assumptions are valid enough to trust the p-values produced by the model. plot() can create up to six plots, three of which are shown below.

par(mfrow = c(1,3)) # par() sets up a plotting grid: 1 row x 3 columns
plot(model, which = c(1,2,5))

  • The 1st plot Residuals vs.Fitted checks for homoscedasticity (aka homogeneity of residual variances). What you do not want to get here is a funnel shape, meaning that the variance increases along increasing fitted points. We do not have anything like that here. The spindle shape its not perfect, but as close as it gets in real life.
  • The 2nd plot Quantile-Quantile Residuals confirms that residuals are normally distributed, albeit not perfectly.
  • The 3rd plot Residuals vs.Leverage is used to identify outliers and high leverage points. Quick glance tells us that there are very few data points that can affect model fit and we should not worry.

Predicting New Data

One advantage of storing regression models as object is for using them to make predictions on new data. New data can come from observations that are not available at the time of model training. To make predictions on new data, use the predict() function.

R is also an object-oriented language, as is a functional one. Model objects in R have associated functions that operate on data stored within them. predict() is one of them.

Lets predict an overall score for a super a left-footed player with dribbling skill of 100. Note that column names must be exactly the same as in the training data.

newData <- tibble(skill_dribbling = 100, preferred_foot = "Left")
predict(model, newdata = newData)
##        1 
## 89.33936
